Fight on the sharp knives: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems clear that it is better to buy just a phone.
There are a lot of reasons to choose a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s hard to get a high-end high-end gramofon at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
However, such music products do not appear on LPs and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if there are vinyles with art rock, jazz or blues on your shelves, you probably dream of such a gramofon at least.
The same is true of music on the go, i.e. compressed music, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also quality and price categories.
For someone, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand yuan for a player, just like a Pink Floyd fan will hardly get a headset for twenty yuan from the marketplace.
There are two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines battery duration.
Some top-of-the-art music players handle much more than just playing music, but what most mobile phones don’t happen to do.
No device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone and video, it can play music and video, both record, has a better, a worse camera, and maybe it can also navigate.
And when we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a little wonder, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can take pictures of anything.
The universality of the mobile also has its disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the display indicator will send you to the charger.
Playing music is one of the greatest sources of energy.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than twelve hours, mostly much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
Therefore, in the case of cheap mobile phones, you will not be able to play for more than a few hours.
If you call here and there, buy one more charger to work for security – this also applies to more expensive devices.
For MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the worse will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on one charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to a memory card, but only a few card readers can handle miniature memory cards that are used in mobile devices without reduction.
You do not need any special software for iPods.
All you need to do is fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create a music library sorted by the name of the performer, the name of the album, the genre or the user rating.
Some devices only display the tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows, and some can both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, operating system smartphones).
Players are easier to operate, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a particular device, pay attention especially to battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, control comfort.
If you listen to music every day for a short time in the tram, you will need any mobile phone that can play MP3.
This can be done by almost any mobile phone.
You don’t even have to watch what music formats your mobile phone or player can.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used, and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in the WMA format.
Less common is AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
You just need to visit the respective website of the operator (or other provider) via the mobile internet and purchase a song or album.
This service itself could already be a good argument for purchasing a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is miserable and is mostly limited to fast-moving radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry a car with them.
Whenever you get a desire to listen to something, your cell phone is stuck in your pocket, while your MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always wear headphones or at least handheld handsfree.
If not, you can take advantage of the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of mobile music will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3 thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns, you can buy a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of output on the regular headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones with a 3.5mm headset can cost up to fifteen thousand.
The main advantage of these devices is, among other things, the ease of use.
The easiest – not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) – players can be controlled by really everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously common cartridge or a gramofon is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of the accidentally turned on mobile internet and subsequently a giant account for data transmission.
Which device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the corresponding card you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and you still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach out to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than €1,100.
If you belong to the more demanding listeners reach for specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
The next is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as independent MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to £4,000, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), you will get MP3 players from the above mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing here – a virtual operator that would force the classic to downplay.
It may not be long missing.
The fact that the Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
It was also that the price of SMS is higher in the UK than in the rest of the world.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
Per this sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and a penetration of more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to cheer on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), has repeatedly stated that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network no longer has too many chances (otherwise, it would probably be hard to look for frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entrance of virtual operators to the mobile market that brought a significant price reduction, to which classical operators had to react.
Even before the entry into the market, such as Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We do not have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among others, U:fona.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not involve relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on an untouched target group can also be quite a good move.
This service is specifically aimed at men.
“The right guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept could be found in Poland as well.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.”
Unfortunately, there is no chance, say mobile operators.
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations don’t look too hopeful.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region,” Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, told Mobil.cz.
It has been stated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything to prevent any potential competitors from emerging.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner, the better.
We have discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Per it is glowing for better times.
The first virtual operator is expected to be available by the end of the year.
For now, however, his creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for the emergence of a full-fledged virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been contacted by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area,” Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telefónica O2 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also referring to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová added in rare agreement with O2: "So far we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further."
And he adds: “In the T-Mobile network, there will be hardly any virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table so that we can think about it in this short term."
Vodafone is focusing its attention on fulfilling the requirements of its 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “We are open to negotiating with potential virtual operators, especially in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial for customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with operators one hand
The movement of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
Why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators are about something, they can pull for one rope, witnesses the hats around the formation of U:fona.
Per the biggest pressure toward the T-Mobile was at the time of the creation of T-Mobile’s U:Fona.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the website.
But now it’s just U:fon that’s a good reason not to allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entrance of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that entering another player would put high demands on him and, above all, on his services.”
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the total disinterest of Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
It is not just the position of the CSTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - has no powers to interfere in economic competition.
These are the responsibilities of the Competition Protection Authority (COPA).
He has taken a typical stance on the whole issue.
“The virtual operator’s entry into the mobile market would be possible after a contract was concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of Foreign Relations of the ÚOHS.
The representatives of the operators are not surprised by this statement.
From the authority, which is to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, this is more than a matter of consideration.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In the overseas, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile phone services.”
Apparently, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the decline in prices does not belong to the interests of the UOHS.
In fact, shocking on the whole case is the touching sympathy of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is just a coincidence comes up on its own.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is only the work of chance and a tough competitive battle.
"The Office has not found signs of anti-competitive behavior in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has no corresponding increased responsibility for their behavior on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
There is, of course, an analysis of relevant markets carried out by the ITU, according to which telecommunications are a single market from the point of view of competition.
Of course, none of these companies have a dominant position in the market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view – for the creation of a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator is always required.
And the mobile operator - it is quite logical - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, it must be dominant in a certain segment.
Even if we did not admit this argument, it should be at least warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding remarkably similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of stakeholders (including GTS Novera) show that when dealing with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
The weighting of responsibility to the CST is then a relatively usual trick in telecommunications, by which the CSTO takes his hand away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted novel of the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of the CSTU to the field of competition in telecommunications did not succeed, although a number of experts promised to improve the situation.
They must know more than well, but their interests are elsewhere.
It happens when no one is watching.
At the same time, unnoticed remains the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, which in Czech mobile networks exists just a few.
They are companies issuing their own tariffs for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
This is usually done by multilevel marketing companies.
Its own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually come only to the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions we were dealing with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," said Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that such actions would not be carried out by responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
However, none of the operators can prevent such a process.
These companies have insignificant profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a small percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not kept on their name, so they can’t dispose of it as regular customers of mobile operators.”
That should be at least strange.
Then another question opens up for the UFO.
If mobile operators are closing their eyes on a similar process, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the UOHS has relatively strong powers to reveal similar activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators' explanation that they have no idea of anything like that and their business conditions prohibit it.
When to be the most expensive
As has been repeated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, traditional operators tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical – too small, possibly too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was in these moments that regulatory authorities intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and the creation of others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the uncertainty of competences is more than suitable for them in these cases.
Do not throw flint into the grain.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If any of the operators has admitted the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain reluctant to reject (discriminate) other interested parties.
And we may stop calling the drag than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where my home.
The hymn was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávka.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choir performance and instrumental version.
The song was sung by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the modifications of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He previously told Czech radio that he has deliberately selected singers with young representative voices that are expressive and popular for singing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care of both and then also the choir to have a clear diction, so that the text is well understood, so that they agree," he said.
The Czech National Anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where my home first sounded in 1834 on the plates of the Stavovsky Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka Josefa Kajetána Tyla supplemented by the music of Františka Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously took it for their own.
After the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the song became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
