Prague MHD on Wednesday for the first time on chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will enter the history of the Prague Transport Enterprise as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, tram and buses who will have an electronic voucher in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, there are approximately 100,000 people who own an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and also let it be uploaded to their chip card in the information centers and workplaces of the Transport Enterprise at the metro stations Museum, Můstek, Holešovice Station, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transportation Enterprise www.dpp.cz.
Over 400 customers have taken advantage of the service in the afternoon.
Those who begin to use the online store can definitely forget about the outlet windows in the metro stations, where they had to regularly stand in long rows for paper tickets.
The coupon is purchased via the Internet and uploaded to an Opencard card at one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"At these locations, passengers are provided with a checkpoint with trained service, which will help interested parties with online shopping and also upload the purchased voucher to their card," said Martin Opatrny, a project spokesman.
In addition to the libraries, it will also be possible to upload electronic coupons to the Opencard in self-service machines, which are mounted in several metro halls.
How do these machines look like?
They are red, they resemble ticket markers and passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," he added.
Check the driver’s place automatically
Managing the machines that will start working tomorrow is simple.
You just need to insert an Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid voucher will be uploaded to it.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its vicinity.
Thus, in the suburban trains and bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, which travel to the capital mainly inhabitants of the central Czech municipalities.
"In the trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, guides are equipped with card readers, using which they determine the time and band validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid, which sets up the schedule of Prague public transport.
Suburban buses have card readers built in the driver’s box.
Therefore, it is necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the specified place on the side of the box.
This way, the driver will check the validity of the uploaded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of the uploaded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel by suburban buses and will not remember when the coupon expires can go back to the self-service machines, where the coupons are uploaded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the device display.
Sudets want U.S. referendum
In 1945, the Sudet Germans demanded that Shumava be incorporated into the United States.
It comes from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Czech Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States.
In 1945, some groups of Sudet Germans appealed to the President of the United States.
This follows, among other things, from the letter, which was preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Czech Scientific Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov ask in a letter to the US president not to allow the return of the "Shumavsky County" - seized by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly and we want to be really sure that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter, signed with the words “People to whom the fate of Shumava lies on the heart.”
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia presumably gives the Sudet Germans - with knowledge of the Czech national nature - hope only of brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter of the American president ask that the Šumava take over a protectorate for present and eternal times.
“We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter-million people, you would give this territory to a country foreign to us, which oppresses and rejects minorities and in no way contributes to the victory of the Allies,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of the revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States allegedly doubts about the mindset of the Schumacher Germans, it would be enough to hold a referendum in the Schumacher County on whether its inhabitants want to become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a little naive in today’s knowledge of post-war history, according to some memorials, it appropriately illustrates the expectations of the Sudet Germans at the time.
