Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals also have emotions.
But how would it be possible to verify whether they feel the same when they behave like us?
In the online magazine "Edge" for several years, contributions of renowned scientists have been published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has yet to prove, when we cannot prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we begin to engage in a different kind and open up the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter into an incompatible terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets into danger, it will do the same as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
People behave in a similar way, which some scientists believe is a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe in this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal experience.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share in short-term memory and execution or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that a person differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the linguistic essence of a person: since so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not matter on language, it would be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, no matter how constructed, would probably differ from most states of consciousness of our own.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out how the consciousness of other animals might look.
When, as something inner and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, it poses great problems to explore it.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically easily accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, developed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
Thus, what we refer to as “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) exploits the operating memory.
Seeing from this angle, feelings are closely associated with those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
In connection with the linguistic nature, there is a subtle graduation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
In contrast, for example, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to physical feelings, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Because this network hasn’t changed much over the course of human evolution, it could be able to participate in the feelings perceived by several animal species.
Theoretically, I cannot object to this, but I consider it unproven.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us as fear in rats and humans is probably felt by both organisms equally: but how can it be verified, Pankseep says, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The swallow is running away from danger—is he also afraid?
In my view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the coincidence of experience.
It’s true that a neural comparison pushes us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but donkeys have no brains.
Is the brain responsible for emotions?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
I really don’t know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and on language), I would rather examine emotional behavior than emotional perception.
Anyway, in this case we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Like rats, I do not examine language and consciousness, nor do I examine feelings, for I do not know if they exist.
It can be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than throw myself against a wall repeatedly.
I am a practical emotionalist.
