The pride and obstacles of black people living in a separate city
Hidden among the rugged amusement parks of the larger Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and enormous, lies a quiet city where the pride and demands of African-American life come to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of quaiwa, two schools, and no prison.”
Now it is a wanderplace.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee come to the annual eatonville festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a side, even though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It’s still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s losing.”
Even today, in a year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open discussion of races, many residents remain cautious of foreign views.
“We pay great attention to how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, who lives here from birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
“It must be right.”
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historic model of black rise and a community of 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shaded example of Southern rural Negro culture – sometimes despised, sometimes praised – which emerged from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the people here are both proud and protective.
And the worries about Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through hearty books full of inscriptions such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of a Florida tour guide have transformed the city into a little bit of Road 17, which leads through the often overlooked center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With a big bubble in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of Eatonville’s first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"Left next to the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he doesn't know much about reading or writing."
She also mentioned Widow Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and anything at all that fits into an hourly hotel.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, re-marriage, and sex.
This was obviously not a typical Fodor’s publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it as it was," says ninety-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's choir girls that Hurston made immortal by quoting men who sang silly songs about their beauty.
“Some people don’t like it,” she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipster who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoked and wore trousers in a city that is still proud of being worthy of dressing.
Most of the inhabitants were fascinated, Franklin said, but many flattered.
“The people of Dawn have always liked to see it,” Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, “she never stayed too long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were discarded from the press.
It seemed that Eatonville and the rest of the world had forgotten about it.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
“I think they didn’t understand its significance to the world or its message at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Officials in Orange County wanted to stretch the city through a five-way highway instead of the Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-way main road.
Orlando climbing has already pushed Interstate Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for mixing races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things on the people who sat on the side," Franklin said.
“There was a woman who was killed.
They threw melons out of the car.
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court’s demand for forced integration and stated that its decision in Brown v. the Chamber of Education was “insulting rather than glorifying to my race.”
Residents now argue that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has diminished cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of youth.
“Black children were used to hugging – I remember it – you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
“You don’t embrace your white teacher because your white teacher – I mean there’s a cultural barrier there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create room for many other Zora Neale Hurston – black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with careless self-esteem and quotes such as “How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I will not understand.”
In 1975, Alice Walker went to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, the acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came to the shelves of the bookstores, re-incorporating her into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just when Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the lights of the ramp again.
Former neighbors of Hurston now regarded her as a savior.
To show what could happen to destroy their highway, the community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many come back to celebrate.
After a few years, the state has withdrawn from the highway project.
“The five streams of the highway have resurrected, you would say directly blown up, a real civil pride,” Nathiri said.
Boyd said it more simply: “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Outside towns like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began to attend the church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a fading street in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today it is 90 percent black.)
With strangers who come to look for the story and meaning of Eatonville, it is still often treated cautiously.
Permission for most interviews is required to have in advance, and certain things — such as wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a brave, self-confident teacher who loves the full red, are still worried that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as Hurston’s festival grew, domestic pride also grew.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and so, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, laborious, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicity.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, eighteen-year-old Edwin Harvey, a sincere love for the village sounds when he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police he says would enjoy some help.
And even the younger, like the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, just going through here, will think, 'Hm, this city is nothing against the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently on Sunday after the church.
"But if you really stop and look for a moment into history, it's a very nice city."
