The Ministry of Internal Affairs requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in their vehicle that prevents them from starting the car when they are drunk or if they do not breathe.
The proposal came to light in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
The aim is to return drivers behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a course of traffic rehearsal.
In addition to the National Office for Traffic Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers accused of driving in drunkenness more than once will sit behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if a higher than the permitted alcohol concentration is recorded.
The price is more than €1,000 and must be paid by the defendant.
A study conducted in this regard in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced infringements by 65% in the first year after introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behavior before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, since legal regulation can be carried out in the usual manner, the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although it has already been test-installed in some industrial cars and public service vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Socialist Workers' Party), which recommends installing this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
