Speaking of Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they are asleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you out, but in reality it’s meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilokvia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly some of you have been told that he spoke from sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fever), or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every several months...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is not a single reason to explain it.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nightmares, nocturnal enuresis (nocturnal pomočing) or moonlight, but it may not be so.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fever, stressful or upset situations.
This is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great strength, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes much anxiety in him and thus manifests itself.
We said it is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by remembering a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before going to bed.
Look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent television programs or series.
For very nervous children and those to whom work can relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more calmly.
When somnilokvia appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that from what happened, the next day he will no longer remember anything.
Useful Advice
Do not be him.
This is useless because he is unconscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if several times in a row it seems to you that he is very worried, it would be advisable to seek advice or find out what causes such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and draw information from him.
It will be useless, because when he is asleep, he is not conscious so that he can arrange his thoughts.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he thinks of and why he says it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
