Interview - Blood That Is Again Certain
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its President, Dr. Francine Décary, was justified by the fact that Héma-Québec has become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the confidence of the public, which was seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is commonly known, the state blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of public resentment, in February 1994, the Canadian government launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee was responsible for this role.
Following Gélineau and Krever’s report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be managed by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
“The situation was devastating.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” he says and proudly adds that by the beginning of 2008 Héma-Québec was already trusted by almost 94% of the Québec population.
However, Dr. Decary does not lose sight of the fact that “confidence is something very fragile.”
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At that time, we witnessed many cases of human-like mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t know if this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau Report, according to which, when we do not know it and when the spread of a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, is at stake, preventive measures should be taken.
In April 1999, we refused blood from people who had stayed in the UK for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was proven that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that it makes sense to stick to the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor blood, rather than the presence of the antibodies on which previously used tests were based.
NAT tests have shortened the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than a week.
This substantially reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without our knowledge.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that before someone gets HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to appear.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for recovery in absolute calm,” said the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what disease-causing element can appear in the system.
Last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by insect bites.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supplies, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies.
“The demands are growing because the population is ageing.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Québécois eligible to donate.”
Every healthy person at least 18 years of age, meeting the criteria of admissibility, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people who donate blood are not accepted on average because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fever runs, they are excluded for a year.
“With these 3% we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Defects are very rare.
However, members of the donor network should be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to donate blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so untouched today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” Francine Decary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000 blood samples from the umbilical cord into the bank and we expect to collect over 1,000 each year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes the program of blood collection from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
