Orwell’s Discourse by Barrick Gold
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwell’s logic, he confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has initiated prosecution against three authors and a poor little publisher for insulting honour in order to provoke “transparent public debate” and demands six million dollars for them.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for insulting honour, but the law.
It is not surprising that Garver completely omits this fundamental distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate to bring down anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the process ends up, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums of money to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a very uneven battle with an army of lawyers supported by the flawless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic in these uneven battles, after all, often consists in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will shut the mouths of the counterparty and, in addition, scare anyone who dares to deal with the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the whole matter to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas, and not in the wounds of the obesity.
Therefore, it was not enough for mining companies to open their books, their documentation, and set up a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole matter.
Barrick Gold, however, appears to have no confidence in the public opinion and is shamelessly rejecting petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Per Garver could explain how he could demand a “public debate” while contempting the opinions of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president’s world only refers to fat-paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, people have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand — or does not want to understand — that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be thrown into the mouth (as part of his prosecution of "public debate" Barrick, by the way, has just submitted an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them that they should stop using this term...).
If we ignore Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to investigate and seek the truth, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
In general, it denies the right to quote trusted sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada it will be impossible to study and discuss topics that do not like the wealthy companies of this world without exposing ourselves to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could form it if it followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada authors.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that despite what he claims, he has no desire to conduct a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as is it for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures to limit this type of unjustified prosecution.
