Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with blue eyes long represented his trumpet, according to others, a weakness.
Has this American actor gone out of narcissism with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unwavering talent that were inherent to him also kept him away from the power category that gives rise to real stars.
What a long run!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 on his ranch in Connecticut due to lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, to whom he was similar and long a kind of film rival, Newman was a more cautious actor, more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful babies.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American Dream.
No exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw the whole country falling in love with the self-made man, a warrior in the Pacific, wounded in a battle, who in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then attended the New York Actor's Studio and celebrated triumphs in the theater, television and soon in film.
The same man, who fought for civil rights, was also a car racer, second in the 1979 Le Mans 24-hour race, and a sex symbol, despite forming an exemplary couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him, the shadowy spots of this hidden, discrete, socially engaged star, allergic to the whisper of their own show business, which will forever remain to some extent mysterious, also leave.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman’s departure this weekend caused dizziness among film lovers, while his big roles compete on the black canvas of memories.
After him, he defiles for more than half a century of constantly changing American Seventh Art.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Burning Roof, an adaptation of Tennessee Williams from 1958.
From a less recent past (1990) we find his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have entered history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, a tortured, violent, unforgettable criminal from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role for James Dean, taken after his death, which made Newman truly known in 1956.
Sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Oscar for best film in 1973.
In The Hustler (1961), he plays the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which brings him the only seven-nominated Oscar in 1987.
This journeying face of ages, it was him.
And again he.
Different periods of his career compete with each other.
Young people know him especially thanks to the iconic Slap Shot by George Roye Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He then ended his career with the role of an Irish mafia baron in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike several film legends, who soon left the craft, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with his glamorousness and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier regarded it, not without humor, as a “living challenge to underplaying,” judging that in his performances he pushed too much on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came like on the bench, the profession was not always so gentle.
The first lovers, however, he played less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, lumpy and desperate, whose falls and rebellions were reflected in his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed the little-known side of his shy sensitivity.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), in which his wife Joanne Woodward played the main role, presents a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
To his son Scott, whom he lost due to an overdose, he dedicated in 1984 the film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness.
In an uproar of tribute to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former co-star Robert Redford (they played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly stated: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main qualities of a deceased actor.
If we ignore his legendary career, he is also a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film, an opponent of the downfall of Hollywood.
We were used to seeing his image on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, which may have seemed quite unpleasant to us, although it was originally a gag.
However, the proceeds from the sale went to his Foundation for Difficult Childhood account.
Newman thus, rather than allowing himself to be stunned by fame, engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing the following sentences: "Always and until the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a brilliant and generous American artist.
And after all, an exemplary citizen.
What was produced at the Zuschlag & spol facturing factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
In addition to other crimes, including counterfeiting of documents, the politician and his associates are charged with fraud committed by a long-term and systematic criminal organization, which has resulted in extremely significant damage.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money raised in public competitions for their own purposes and often proved the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and local governments – a total of approximately 65 million forints – went partly to the box office of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method, which it also informed the investigating authority, was that the funds obtained in public tenders were collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no actual compensation and never received the commitments taken by the association.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were fake.
The printing of these invoices came from the Józefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies on which the production of invoices is to be carried out were decided, among other things, on the tour of the northern shore of Balaton, to which the Istvan Ladose János Zuschlag sent.
According to his testimony, he was first appointed to look out for pensions and restaurants.
In them he requested accounts for his consumption, according to which the models were then produced invoices submitted within the framework of public competitions issued, inter alia, by the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, and the Capital Government.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados with his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
During his “study journey,” Lados looked for one cellar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its partners in 2003, this hospitality facility provided catering for a group of 90 members from Biztos Pont.
However, so many people, according to the head of the company, would not enter this facility at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was full of formal and content errors.
The pension in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet there were one hundred and thirty guests on the invoice.
However, the rich-fantastic printers exaggerated this even when they listed a company dedicated to the same hospitality - Pigal s.r.o., in whose accounting, according to the information provided to the Prosecutor's Office, the documents sounding at the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even figure.
The head of the company Győző Farkas told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and our tax number were stamped in the wrong place."
As he added, in addition to the formalities, it did not agree that according to the invoice they accommodated a hundred people, because they have only eleven rooms, which do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, food was also listed on the invoice, while their restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
The ardent producers of invoices did not convince themselves that the visited Budapest travel agency organizes only foreign trips, and on the invoice with cash payment, which also did not coincide with the invoice practice of the company, they foolishly referred to as a travel agency in Hungary.
Furthermore, as it emerged during the investigation, they also indicated VAT in the document, although the organization of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
Four documents issued to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s. r. o. disagreed, among other things, with the amount of VAT. The company’s activities were not subject to the above mentioned 25 percent, but 15 percent VAT, and the hotel staff issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "publishers" corrupted the invoice, for example, by stating that one company, as revealed by the prosecution investigation, carried out the road transport of goods, which the company originally based on investment advice did not carry out.
In addition, the fact that the invoices issued by the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont associations are fake has also been collapsed due to formal deviations – the invoice format and the false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Sport Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not notice that HIB s.r.o. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when a group from the Fiatal Városért association dined with it, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
Consciously issued invoices
The second group of invoicers are those who knew they were going to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation issued accounts worth approximately four million forints for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Socialisták.
According to the indictment, the head of the company Collab s.r.o. was forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused Ludovic Györfi.
Biogate s.r.o. also cooperated with Zuschlag and its partners, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations with invoices worth approximately five million forints, behind which there was no actual economic activity.
Not even the movement of money, because the created invoices were later cancelled, which, however, the organizations forgot to state in their documents.
The other group of invoicing companies included those that had ties to the accused.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the representative of the Ukrainian operator of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company dealing with fuel and motor vehicle trading, headquartered in Budapest, where no company can be found.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 for sales of computing equipment worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the data obtained by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by the Kiskunhalas company Cash Investment s.r.o., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The company’s manager was a man from Romania, to whom Ivan Kubatov had also handed over documents relating to the company in 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that on behalf of the company he issued invoices to the associations Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and himself accepted their compensation.
Explicitly at the request of Ivan Kubatov, the Romanian wallworkers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment k.s.
In fact, none of the companies worked, according to the accused, because they did not get a job.
Nevertheless, the companies benefited him by issuing invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció affiliated with Zuschlaga at the request of his co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, who also prepared their founding documents.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave the organizations a total of 15 invoices worth 14.2 million forints.
The Prosecutor’s Office found that Kubatov received 10 percent of the amounts stated on the invoices and VAT.
To issue fictitious invoices, this time for a tender for Biztos Pont, the man also used the company Szi-Beri k.t.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals for a tender by the Mihálye Táncsicse Foundation (TMA), a socialist party public benefit organization.
They earned 500,000 forints each, but did not spend the amounts on the objectives set out in the proposals.
To avoid this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s.r.o.
These invoices were found during a home search in the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
During the hearing, part of the defendants will probably describe the course of the invoice production, as they have already done at the prosecutor’s office.
It may be more interesting if the main accused János Zuschlag decides to reveal everything himself.
His previous statement is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to explain everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, the Socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it on.
He could still be offended, as his requests to mitigate the conditions of his detention, namely to be placed in house arrest, have not yet been heard.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes who have inflicted much greater damage, which they have not yet paid, are free to walk around or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he has no such possibility.
Psychology of Trumping: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalu goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been revealed by researchers from the Neuroscience and Economics Department of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lag behind in an eBay auction competition, so they’d rather pay too much.
Research using an experimental auction attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a game auction, using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method to examine the active brain regions of the subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, the important element of which is to overthrow the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensely when losing.
This brain region, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price screw can be explained by an attempt to avoid a sharp striat reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists conducted a cross-sectional financial investigation.
Three groups were offered against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
Members of another group were also promised that if they came out of the game victoriously, they would receive another $15 in reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but lost the money in the event of a loss.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was that one was emphasized a win and the other a loss.
However, members of the group playing against the loss were willing to go higher than in the control and “win-win” group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
Until now, they explained the phenomena observed at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped us solve the contradiction between the two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York’s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characteristic of liver inflammation and jaundice, but the cause of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen, spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against the A and B viruses, against type C vaccine does not exist.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
Then yellowing, lightened stools and darkened urine will form on the skin and eyelids, and treatment may take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious type of this disease, from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten infected people is treated with medication.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys liver cells callously, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention and regular screening are very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than the average: among people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his doctor if he notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With timely detection, the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infectiousness and preventing cancer.
World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on September 30th, which was first held worldwide in 2004.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God does not suffer?
According to recent research, belief in God works as a kind of analgesic that may have made death easier for Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, investigating how a person's belief in a god affects the perception of pain, the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholics and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of thoroughly examining the human brain, the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first of a series of studies in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from various parts of the university also participate.
The test was carried out by attaching a scintillating instrument to the test subject’s left hand, which produced electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to look closely at two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary dating from the 17th century and the Lady of Leonard da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would bring about a certain state of piety among the believers, while the Da Vinci painting was chosen because it did not differ much from the first and appeared reassuring.
The subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electro-shocks in four consecutive sections, while watching the image separately with a religious or general theme.
Catholics that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe”, as if they were “cared for” and “reassured, filled with peace.”
They felt 12 percent less pain when they watched a religious-themed picture than when they had Leonard’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any highly impressive image even in atheists, only to find the right photo.
"We would have to find a picture that they will see very positively, from the position of the mother or father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practicing faith should change, and in many cases it will change, our personality," Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the pain regulation of believers if they were shown some madonna by Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would a look at the quality of the Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share.
On its tenth birthday, Google can state that people can find it in their pockets at least as well as in the sky above their heads; they know where they’ve been on vacation, what expert examinations they’re going for, and what they’re interested in.
According to Eric Schmidt, one of the chief executives of the company, this is still not enough.
However, as far as skeptics are concerned, making a parallel to Orwell’s dark vision, the very essence of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently stated to the Financial Times that the main goal of Google is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary in order for the founders of Google to stick to their original intention, which was: "Let's arrange all the information in the world!"
According to a spokesman for Google, even after ten years of worldwide work, the company is only at the beginning of working with all the information.
Asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as “what am I going to do tomorrow?” or “what work would actually work for me?” – such seemingly simple questions, however, software won’t be able to answer until they know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that during internet searches the searches are accurately captured, as well as from which IP address it was searched and to which pages the interested parties moved after the search.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their surfing history, look back at what they have sought and what they have clicked on, thanks to which in the long term finds are generated more directly tailored to them - the same logic will be based on the Recommendations service, through which the system will offer products and services based on the previously mentioned and preserved preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I’m dealing with? – users who are scared when they look at Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, the scope of the potential power represented by the company is more threatening, the counter-reaction does not arouse in Internet users guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all the search terms are not only captured, but in justified cases they can also be issued to a third party, in such legal cases the personal rights of Internet users do not protect anything.
The most well-known example in recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that enabled the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community sites established through it.
Internet users who are concerned about personal rights, however, could still breathe in May, when the firm hand in hand with the e-rights protection organization EFF successfully proved its truth in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be forced by any article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully defeated fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms, which it obtained with reference to the reinforcement of the Children’s Protection Act adopted years ago, yet it failed to get the lists of individual users’ search items, respectively, complete lists of websites and keywords covering a two-month period.)
The view on Google is so contradictory: it is beaten by those who fear disclosure of their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be harmed by starting to use Google’s services, and stand against it with revolt, as belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its wildness, gathering around enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, appearing in many countries, see a new generation of big companies in him, the “corporation that now fricts,” unlike his rival Microsoft, considered to conquer the world because of Windows, though they both fight for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require an identification code from its users and does not want money from them for its applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information and a package of programs acts as much more accessible, younger, "cooler" than the practice of the official software giant.
However, this may also be due to the fact that geeks understand exactly the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personal rights, which has brought with it one of the most famous keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
In fact, the Web 2.0 is nothing more than collaboration, about the fact that we deliberately leave traces behind and use the communication channels that we have at our disposal, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can maintain a profile on several community sites from Facebook to Xang, which he can easily connect with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app, recording his listened music, all this can then connect to navigation systems, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and can write a blog on which his latest photo galleries will automatically appear, which he stores on Flickr or Picasa.
At the same time, we can read about a lot of exemplary cases: a girlfriend in the morning, looking at a flood of photos of common friends, easily finds out with whom her shitty boyfriend spent the evening, or the company can fire her employee just because she outlines her honest opinion about top management on her blog: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has been completely re-evaluated today.
The one who lives an online life consists of what it shows out, so we could define the basic thesis hiding behind the behavior of today’s youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something or at least avoid Google’s monopoly has the option (starting with Scroogles, who uses Google’s search engine, but does not intentionally leave traces).
Google’s online apps from text editor to photo editor and news portal can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and which do not make us the best possible profile.
Public opinion is not very secretly expecting when Google will show the teeth.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces threaten advertising agency investments, and services deployed at an ever-accelerating rate seriously disrupt the lives of not only Microsoft, but also numerous other software designers.
Critical observers, however, also find counter-points that make a disturbing impression: the top management, for example, completely rejected employees' protests after raising the corporate kindergarten fee to double, any frequent daily meals of employees were too expensive, according to the company's management, but all this is lost in addition to the fact that Google even in 2006 bowed before the Chinese government and, according to their agreement, filters out any findings that cause good taste, respectively, the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company’s internal rules is that it never advertises new services in advance until they can be used, but it’s certain that the expected problems of the coming months and years may overwhelm the world in new places: while some believe that Google’s project to scan and archive books and magazines is gaining such size that the company will soon have to deal with the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear its Health system, in which we can build a complete own health profile with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google builds a genetic database can then serve as a good starting material for the next generation of sci-fi writers, Cory Doctorow’s famous novel “Scroogled” describes with Orwell’s reminiscences a future in which one can approach man scaryly well only with the help of data from Google.
