Intelligent car imitates flight
What would probably be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the CEATEC in Japan, was inspired by Nissan engineers who were involved in building a new generation of collision-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has developed the BR23C biomimetic robotic steering system, a robotic mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate any collisions.
“During flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective envelope,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s chief executive for technological PR and R&D.
The compound eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, the engineers came up with the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters ahead of the BR23C in a 180-degree field, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is caught within a fraction of a second, then the robot car begins to mimic the movements of the bee and, by turning the wheels in the range necessary to prevent a collision, immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
“If it didn’t, a robotic car’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Tošijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
They must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety protective envelope, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of the eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or angularly, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding them, the robotic car has only used the possibility of rotating, accelerating and slowing.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, instinctive, intelligent response is important, not processing ability, let alone data storage.
This mechanism has to process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
He doesn’t need to store them and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so he constantly uses only a few kilobyte memory.
It does not require a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of an instantaneous avoidance technology that, according to Nissan’s estimates, could get into mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another option could be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which would, after avoiding obstacles in the way, lead the driver to the specified final destination.
The baby has a name already.
The $700 billion bailout package, which is to be divided into several repayments and aimed at buying back low-quality loans from banks, is already in written form.
In the first round, half of the amount will be used.
After further talks, which ended on Saturday after midnight, Congress officials reached an agreement in a few days-long debate on a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters.
“We’ve made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic chairwoman of the House of Representatives, saying it’s only about signing an agreement.
The deal was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson said of the compromise: “The program will work and be effective, but further steps need to be taken.”
The written version of the package was released before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. (Washington time) (i.e. Monday at 2 p.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise in the stock markets.
The draft legislation entitled the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, which is to be established on the agenda, will be voted first by the House of Representatives on Monday, and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday evening, after which the news of the deal was also welcomed in the White House.
“We are pleased with the progress we have made last night and greatly appreciate both sides’ efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
The program, after all, differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which meant that a total of $700 billion would be spent on the repurchase of low-quality securities secured by mortgages.
It is now possible to spend in the first round a maximum of half the amount of 700 billion, and that 250 billion will be used immediately after Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, and the Treasury Department will buy securities secured by mortgages that are rated as poor quality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the decision of the president.
The program will be supervised by a special board, a member of which will also be the President of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The second half of the $700 billion will depend on a further decision by Congress.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy back low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other “toxic” loans.
The purchase can be carried out in the framework of auctions and directly, the competent officials of the Ministry said.
The legal norm will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee on funds that are reasonable for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary means to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system, spending up to $700 billion, whether it be large-scale purchases of bad funds, their insurance, or preventing the systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major monetary institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
Bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting for help from the state, on the contrary, can count on the government reducing their departure fees – which is simply called “golden parachute” in overseas slang.
The limitation of their payments will only occur in certain cases, in addition, these limitations will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry buys as part of an auction, gold parachutes will be taxed if the falling bank executives are not retired straight away.
In the case of direct repurchase of low-quality loans, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the money for management is not exaggerated.
It should be added that the existing gold parachute contracts will not change, the restriction will only apply to new contracts, which is to be an additional incentive to participate in the program.
"This is the first case in U.S. history where legal restrictions on the remuneration of CEOs will come into effect," said Barney Frank, the chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state will have the right to obtain a share in the banks participating in the program, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, since once the economy and the rescued bank stand up, they can make a profit from the transaction.
In the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress on how the expected financial sector losses can be reimbursed to taxpayers.
Of course, there were voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
“We were not asked for this by American citizens, because this won’t protect taxpayers’ dollars,” said Darrell Issa, a Republican congressman from California.
His Ohio Democratic counterpart, Mary Kaptur, believes that those who were responsible for the collapse of Wall Street urged the bill to be adopted.
Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic sales prices in industry increased by 0.1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month, then by 12.9% compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office.
Export sales prices in the industry were higher by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent annually.
Manufacturing prices in the industry, as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices, were higher by 0.7% compared to the previous month, increasing by 3.2% annually.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased compared to the previous month only a minimum of 0.1 percent.
Also, domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2,8 percent), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing of bracelet and peasant products by 4.6 percent, and the production of footwear by 2.5 percent, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials has caused a significant monthly price rise in the chemical materials and products industry (1,6 percent).
Prices dropped in the oil processing sector (1,4 per cent), the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0,9 per cent), as well as – to a minimum extent – in the wood processing sector (0,1 per cent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities remained unchanged.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 to 0.9 percent.
In the production and distribution sector of electricity, gas and water, which has a large weight in the domestic sales of industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continued influence of the officially determined increase in gas prices taking place since July 1.
In the twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in the individual sectors of the processing industry, prices increased the most in the specialized oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical sector, prices increased by 13.2 percent, in the food, beverage and tobacco sector, which has a decisive weight, then by 11 percent.
Prices dropped in the textile and textile products sectors (2.5 percent) and in the electrical machinery and appliances sector (0.3 percent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the production and distribution sectors of electricity, gas and water exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of division by sector focus, in August, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the sectors dealing with the production of tangible assets.
In the consumer goods sectors prices rose by 0.3 percent, while in the energy processing and further processing sectors prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was in August 2008 in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8 percent).
In consumer goods industries, prices increased by 6.8 percent, while in material assets prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 per cent in a twelve-month comparison.
Within a month, our domestic currency weakened 1.7 percent against the euro, 7.1 percent against the dollar, 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar compared to August 2007.
