“The vast majority of young Roma do not have a secondary education, and because of the poor quality of primary education, only a small percentage of them can higher education.”
Járóková further stressed that education as a fundamental human right has a key role in applying other human rights.
Investing in early childhood education for Roma children can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
It is necessary to strengthen the awareness of these contexts in the broadest circles - between Roma and non-Roma children.
The sooner a Roma student starts school, the more likely they will be to become a productive member of the labour market; they contribute to the national budget through income taxes and excise taxes.
“It is the right of their European Union citizenship for Roma to ensure the right to quality education and to guarantee the elimination of their less-quality and separate education,” said Lívia Járóková.
