"This scientific opinion suggests that 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable music devices for at least five years, more than an hour a week and keep the device at high volume, risk permanent loss of hearing ability."
“It worries me that so many young people who often use portable music devices and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unwittingly damage their hearing in irreparable ways,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“The scientific findings – continues the leader – indicate a clear risk and need to react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to encourage consumers and disclose this information.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding to make them fully effective and keep pace with new technology.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine this issue in light of the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
“The researchers confirm that concerns need to be made and now the European Commission will examine, together with other members and parties who have raised the problem, what measures could eventually be introduced to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable music instruments and similar devices.”
