Elites in Danger
This phenomenon came to light a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout proposed by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested and interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, milder, friendly to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is on the contrary conservative, hostile to “them from Washington” and to the world of finance, strong especially in the central and southern states.
The soul that arrogantly expressed itself in the vote I talked about at the beginning.
But this just quoted thing is just an example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake already shows: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and not only here.
Both in the U.S. and in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, which are thickening in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactualization, the extraordinary revival of the market, the double category State-power in relation to a certain nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but which primarily involve the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This has created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically worldwide, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be substantially out of play or that it has nothing to add: the European Union, which is, as always, divided between different interests and different state strategies, and which is unable to choose for a single common political line, has given an obvious proof.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each state, the rescue plans, the recovery of the market, the new rules and, most importantly, the distribution of funds: in a moment when we get into distress, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources to be able to try to put everything in order.
And they also have the necessary means and authority to use them: two resources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of in a similar extent.
This new emphasis, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, after all, in perfect accord with the ever-increasing importance, which tries to attribute recent economic progress to one factor closely linked to it: territorial jurisdiction.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the web, an increasingly sophisticated technology, the intangible, while we were convinced that global finance was already predestined to rule the world, from nowhere we realized that our future, on the contrary, will have to face more and more with such little intangible things as water, grain, oil.
All things, whoever would say so, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are in any case connected, absolutely, to a confined space, territory.
So, whoever becomes their ruler is sure to have much more cards in his sleeve than whoever is not, and whoever is unlucky to live in a place without grain, without diesel, and without water.
I come to the second novella, which, however, predicts the evil.
Whoever speaks of territory, state, government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, of leadership.
Given the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to arise.
On the one hand, the realization that objectively there is a need for authoritative leadership, a request for someone who would be able to grasp the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discreditation towards existing leadership, especially economic, which has proved to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark spots.
And together something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: discreditation, impatience, feeling incompetent and absent, which are trying to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
In fact, it seems to spread more and more in the broad masses of the population the belief that their actions are the same as the ideas of the so far popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already surpassed its time and is indifferent to the views of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, nourishes a branch underground, but the strong movement to eliminate the ruling classes and the traditional political arrangement is manifested in sudden electoral “rejection” or in unexpected changes in collective moods in recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of the Labourists in the UK, to the uprising U.S. Congressmen against Bush (and the victory of the right in Italy).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, someone would say their format, have increasing difficulties to understand, that is, to represent, which, not from today, is forming in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinforcing, growing, potentially too cloudy.
Before this, it would be exaggerated to speak of a permanent “mass rebellion”.
But we can’t say that it means having eyes open.
