“It’s as if we lost a friend, a friend with whom we shared a piece of journey and a lot of emotions,” feels the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won Tornator an Oscar twenty years ago and the grand prize of the jury in Cannes, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness for the way of life that the cinema probably lost forever.
The values obtained by Anecem, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 cinemas of traditional type have closed their doors, and the highest bill has been paid primarily by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna ranks first with the loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
